Lest you forget, a computer is simply a tool to get the work done. Speaking
as one in a small business, all I care is that my memos & letters go out
looking professional, my AR and AP are current, Payroll is made and taxes
are paid!
	That's what the vast majority of computers are being used for. Frankly,
It's good to see some standards. Without them, noone would see some of the 
neat stuff available now. Remember the lat '70's? I don't have enough
fingers on my hands to count the number of standards that existed just a 
decade ago. Yesterday, it was CPM. Today, its MS-DOS. Who knows what the
next one will be. Most important, as a programmer, standards keep me from having
to reinvent the wheel every time a new widget comes out.
	Yesterday, I installed MSDOS 5.0 on my Mother-in-Laws XT. Guess what?
Standards allowed it to run. If Gates decided to mak MSDOS X.XX not run on
previous generation machines, he certainly could have (other manufactures did:
ie Apple, Rat Shack, Comodore).
	Most importantly, standards actually help you as a hacker. What frame
of reference would you use to discuss a particular programming problem? We
already have problems with system hangs on "standard" equipment now. 

	I do agree that these standards must be decided by groups such as ACM
and IEEE. That's the venue for those discussions not in corporate board rooms.
The problem: as slow as our trade organizations move (no standards yet for C++),
businesses like Borland and MicroSoft will grab the chance and FILL CONSUMER
NEEDS. That's what this computer stuff is all about

Mark Evans, ST2BX@jetson.uh.edu


