Well, this is true in a sense, if you work in a vacuum you can
use whatever OS you want. Hell, you can write your own.

However, if you want to produce software for people to use on PCs and 
want to sell it and make money, then you had better write it for MSDOS 
(or MSDOS/Windows, maybe NT in the future). Admittedly there are 
exceptions. 

The same is true if you want to use commercial software. (Sure I'm 
aware that many versions of Unix, Linux and OS/2 will run some DOS 
programs. But none of them will run all DOS programs). 

None of this has anything to do with whether I personally like MS-DOS, 
Windows or Windows NT. Fact is, Microsoft basically owns the PC OS 
market. 

Personally, I have Linux running on my PC. Great OS. For what I do
with it, I do have a choice. But many people don't.

