In article <1sb1f2$e5t@terminator.rs.itd.umich.edu> honey@citi.umich.edu writes:
>Evans, Mark A. writes:
>|> 	Yesterday, I installed MSDOS 5.0 on my Mother-in-Laws XT. Guess what?
>|> Standards allowed it to run.
>
>you are confusing standardization with monopolistic control. 


I don't see the monopolistic control.

It is not Microsoft's standard that lets MSDOS run on any PC compatible,
it's all of the hardware manufacturers that are building systems to adhere
to the IBM-PC standard. 80x86, ISA, VGA, IDE, etc may not be the best 
hardware standards to follow, but there are hundreds of PC clone 
manufacturers, all following these standards, which allows me to go
down to the software store and buy any PC-compatible software, and 
reasonably expect it to run on my PC. 

Of course, with MS-DOS, one can reliably run only one application at a 
time, but no one is forcing me to run MS-DOS, there are many alternatives: 
OS/2, DR-DOS, Linux, Windows NT, BSD386, Solaris386, etc. (I chose OS/2). 

No one is forced to buy a PC-compatible either, but many feel it gives
the best performance and software availability for the price. There are
a lot of other choices, such as Apple, Commodore, NeXT, Sun, etc,
but thanks to the competition among the many PC-clone manufacturers,
the price of PC clones stays quite low, while still providing
reasonable performance for most personal computing purposes.

If there really was a hardware or software monopoly, there wouldn't be
such a wide variety of choices of hardware/software. 

